But I'm going to start now,

00:01:18.776 --> 00:01:21.146
because we all have
Tim in our mind.

00:01:21.186 --> 00:01:27.856
But I got into this whole
thing because of Tim.

00:01:27.886 --> 00:01:29.816
I was a college student
who was really interested

00:01:29.816 --> 00:01:32.606
in climate change, because
that was the issue that I felt

00:01:32.606 --> 00:01:33.956
like was the issue of our times.

00:01:33.956 --> 00:01:35.766
And in a way I still do,

00:01:36.116 --> 00:01:38.726
but I hadn't ask the question
what actually lights me up

00:01:39.076 --> 00:01:40.376
and what gets my heart going.

00:01:40.706 --> 00:01:42.926
And in conversations,
Tim really saw

00:01:43.256 --> 00:01:44.996
that food was what lit me up.

00:01:44.996 --> 00:01:47.556
And so he said, "Hey,
there's this food conference,

00:01:47.956 --> 00:01:49.156
called Food and Community.

00:01:49.386 --> 00:01:49.986
You should come.

00:01:49.986 --> 00:01:51.216
Just check it out.

00:01:51.586 --> 00:01:52.786
It'll be fine.

00:01:52.786 --> 00:01:54.106
I know your climate change.

00:01:54.106 --> 00:01:55.206
It's just four days."

00:01:56.376 --> 00:02:01.196
And now 10 years later,
it's been my whole career.

00:02:01.586 --> 00:02:04.556
And one of the reasons why
I wanted to say that is

00:02:05.256 --> 00:02:10.686
because it takes a deeply
spiritual level of humility

00:02:11.116 --> 00:02:15.036
to be that person that sticks
with a community and an issue

00:02:15.346 --> 00:02:22.926
for decades, and supports the
shiny objects that America likes

00:02:22.986 --> 00:02:25.896
to grab on to like me, people
of color who are articulate,

00:02:26.156 --> 00:02:28.226
who are charismatic,
who like the stage.

00:02:29.096 --> 00:02:31.666
But the people who support
us, who get us started,

00:02:31.666 --> 00:02:35.266
who were the ones pushing us
every time we need pushing,

00:02:35.756 --> 00:02:36.646
are people like Tim.

00:02:37.306 --> 00:02:39.736
So for me, he is
one of my teachers.

00:02:40.526 --> 00:02:44.176
And I just wanted to have make
sure that we were all clear,

00:02:44.456 --> 00:02:47.526
I know whose shoulders I stand
on and I'm very, very grateful

00:02:47.526 --> 00:02:49.376
to Tim and I'm grateful to
Katy Menard [assumed spelling]

00:02:49.686 --> 00:02:52.066
because both of them were
the ones that helped push me

00:02:52.466 --> 00:02:53.376
into where I am right now.

00:02:54.616 --> 00:03:02.336
So, moving on from there, I
wanted to help set some context

00:03:02.456 --> 00:03:04.396
because this conference
is beautiful.

00:03:04.576 --> 00:03:07.406
It's an inaugural conference,
we're coming together

00:03:07.406 --> 00:03:10.966
for the first time and I
wasn't meant to come up here

00:03:10.966 --> 00:03:12.466
and do the death and doom story.

00:03:12.466 --> 00:03:15.116
I meant to come up here
and be a storyteller.

00:03:15.696 --> 00:03:17.756
I'm meant to come up here
and make sure that we're all

00:03:17.756 --> 00:03:20.106
in the same page when it
comes to the complexity

00:03:20.486 --> 00:03:22.086
and the significance
of food justice.

00:03:23.166 --> 00:03:26.666
So when thinking about that,

00:03:26.866 --> 00:03:28.786
what is food insecurity
looks like worldwide?

00:03:28.786 --> 00:03:32.246
How many people in the
world are food insecure?

00:03:33.246 --> 00:03:36.936
805 million people are
food insecure in the world.

00:03:37.026 --> 00:03:40.006
And that's about one
in nine people, right?

00:03:40.006 --> 00:03:42.656
And then you bring that
back to the United States,

00:03:43.286 --> 00:03:46.636
one in six people in the United
States are food insecure.

00:03:46.716 --> 00:03:49.026
And the most food
insecure household

00:03:49.026 --> 00:03:51.246
in the United States,
are black women.

00:03:52.076 --> 00:03:54.496
Black single mothers
specifically,

00:03:54.916 --> 00:03:56.106
which tells you a
little something

00:03:56.106 --> 00:03:59.366
about the factors contributing
to food insecurity other

00:03:59.366 --> 00:04:01.596
than just lack of
access to food.

00:04:02.436 --> 00:04:05.076
And finally, one of the
most important things

00:04:05.076 --> 00:04:06.506
about being food insecure is

00:04:06.506 --> 00:04:08.696
that diet-related disease
tends to take you out.

00:04:09.456 --> 00:04:17.666
So 13.2% of African-Americans
have diabetes.

00:04:17.666 --> 00:04:20.166
And African-Americans are
nearly two times is likely

00:04:20.166 --> 00:04:23.906
to have diabetes than
average white American.

00:04:23.906 --> 00:04:27.446
And I'm going to get in to
storytelling in a little bit

00:04:27.446 --> 00:04:28.996
when it comes to
my personal story

00:04:29.546 --> 00:04:34.846
but these statistics translate
into people's cousins,

00:04:34.896 --> 00:04:39.016
their parents, their aunts,
their uncles, it's a real thing.

00:04:39.466 --> 00:04:42.696
Diet-related disease in my
family has been a real thing.

00:04:44.186 --> 00:04:47.586
So, what does this look
when it comes to families?

00:04:48.726 --> 00:04:51.906
The beginning of my personal
story starts with my father.

00:04:52.876 --> 00:04:55.526
My father grew up on
welfare in Los Angeles

00:04:56.166 --> 00:04:59.096
in the late 1950s
or early 1960s.

00:04:59.536 --> 00:05:02.826
And one the things that I
always notice about my dad

00:05:02.826 --> 00:05:03.646
when I was growing up,

00:05:03.646 --> 00:05:06.326
is the fact that he always
had food going, right?

00:05:06.706 --> 00:05:09.066
Wake up on Saturday
morning, he's cooking.

00:05:09.236 --> 00:05:11.316
Come home after school,
there's food.

00:05:11.316 --> 00:05:14.686
Food, food, food, food, food,
food was a thing for him.

00:05:14.686 --> 00:05:17.926
And it was only when I
got older that I realized

00:05:17.926 --> 00:05:20.076
that the other people
that I knew

00:05:20.076 --> 00:05:23.596
that treated food the way my
dad did were a lot of my friends

00:05:23.596 --> 00:05:24.696
who were from Central America.

00:05:25.346 --> 00:05:28.226
My Guatemalan friends,
my Mexican friends,

00:05:28.226 --> 00:05:32.116
my El Salvadorian friends,
some of my Vietnamese friends,

00:05:32.766 --> 00:05:35.686
some of my Afghani friends,
and I was trying to figure

00:05:35.686 --> 00:05:38.576
out what was this thread,
what was this thing

00:05:38.576 --> 00:05:39.776
that I felt was in common?

00:05:40.606 --> 00:05:42.136
And I started talking
to them about it.

00:05:42.836 --> 00:05:45.786
And one thing that came up
was that all of these friends

00:05:45.786 --> 00:05:47.586
that I mentioned, their
parents were immigrants,

00:05:48.976 --> 00:05:53.486
and all of their parents fled
situations in their countries,

00:05:54.306 --> 00:05:56.996
and all of their parents
had to do with being hungry.

00:05:57.456 --> 00:06:00.986
So feeding people for them was
not just you need to have food.

00:06:01.236 --> 00:06:08.346
Feeding people for them was this
is a basic, basic valuable thing

00:06:08.346 --> 00:06:09.946
and I am nourishing you,

00:06:11.466 --> 00:06:14.046
nourishing your body,
nourishing your soul.

00:06:14.596 --> 00:06:17.146
Ethnic people have a very
deep relationship with food,

00:06:17.666 --> 00:06:19.146
which is something
I'm going to get into.

00:06:20.056 --> 00:06:24.276
But I want you to think about
what the implications are

00:06:25.096 --> 00:06:26.386
when you can't be nourished,

00:06:27.856 --> 00:06:29.696
when you have trouble
nourishing yourself,

00:06:30.076 --> 00:06:32.126
when you have trouble
nourishing your children,

00:06:32.556 --> 00:06:35.416
when you have trouble nourishing
your spouse and your parents,

00:06:35.856 --> 00:06:37.016
if you're an adult breadwinner.

00:06:37.806 --> 00:06:40.806
I used the word nourish because
food insecurity doesn't quite

00:06:40.846 --> 00:06:41.346
do it.

00:06:42.076 --> 00:06:44.826
The word nourishment
actually gets

00:06:44.826 --> 00:06:48.826
to the multi-dimensional
way that food feeds us.

00:06:48.826 --> 00:06:51.656
And it feeds much more
than just our bodies.

00:06:53.116 --> 00:06:58.036
So to demonstrate this, I wanted
to share a bit of my food story.

00:06:59.636 --> 00:07:01.496
What was the first
food that I ate?

00:07:02.816 --> 00:07:06.116
It was the in utero
nutrients that I was sucking

00:07:06.156 --> 00:07:07.766
through the umbilical
cord from my mom.

00:07:08.036 --> 00:07:14.026
And to be clear about how
hardcore my mother is,

00:07:14.606 --> 00:07:19.736
before she got pregnant she put
my father on a diet in addition

00:07:19.736 --> 00:07:24.966
to herself because she wanted
the moment of conception to be

00:07:24.966 --> 00:07:29.276
as healthy and as pure and
as rich as humanly possible.

00:07:30.426 --> 00:07:34.576
She said "Oh no, our baby need
to start right" to be clear,

00:07:34.736 --> 00:07:36.506
this is what she eating
because we're going

00:07:36.506 --> 00:07:38.286
to start getting
pregnant in about a week.

00:07:38.846 --> 00:07:43.396
And then as she was pregnant
she ate really healthy food.

00:07:43.396 --> 00:07:45.746
She functionally ate a
microbiotic diet, right.

00:07:45.746 --> 00:07:46.816
That's what I grew up eating.

00:07:47.056 --> 00:07:49.886
There was a grain, there was a
vegetable, there was a protein,

00:07:50.146 --> 00:07:53.506
in different parts of the
plate and not really mixing.

00:07:53.506 --> 00:07:56.346
And then occasionally, we
would have enchiladas, right?

00:07:56.656 --> 00:07:59.886
But my mom was really simple
in the way that she cooked.

00:08:00.346 --> 00:08:01.846
And she was very, very healthy.

00:08:02.666 --> 00:08:06.376
So, when I was breastfeeding,
I was getting only the best.

00:08:06.896 --> 00:08:09.296
When I started eating solid
food, she was the type

00:08:09.336 --> 00:08:11.226
that would blend her own
baby food in the blender.

00:08:11.966 --> 00:08:13.646
Only the best, right?

00:08:13.646 --> 00:08:16.726
And when we grow up, there
was this message about sugar.

00:08:17.646 --> 00:08:20.696
You are never to eat it,
it is terrible for you.

00:08:20.916 --> 00:08:25.186
But if you're really good,
you can have a treat.

00:08:25.186 --> 00:08:27.546
And to us, a treat
was the raisin bran

00:08:27.546 --> 00:08:29.746
with the sugar crystals on the
raisins, you know what I mean?

00:08:29.936 --> 00:08:33.136
That was a treat to us instead
of the regular raisin bran

00:08:33.136 --> 00:08:34.446
that kind of tasted
like cardboard.

00:08:35.086 --> 00:08:39.896
But we got the message pretty
early, that there are good foods

00:08:40.066 --> 00:08:41.166
and there are bad foods.

00:08:42.186 --> 00:08:44.706
Now, when I got a little
older, I tried to figure

00:08:44.706 --> 00:08:46.366
out where did that come from?

00:08:46.626 --> 00:08:49.156
You know, I set my mom down and
I said what was this obsession

00:08:49.156 --> 00:08:52.696
that you had with sugar
and with eating healthy

00:08:52.866 --> 00:08:55.466
and with making sure
that we eat healthy?

00:08:55.546 --> 00:08:57.526
Some thing must have
influenced you, yeah?

00:08:58.486 --> 00:09:01.006
And she said, "Yeah.

00:09:01.146 --> 00:09:02.106
Yeah, it did."

00:09:02.916 --> 00:09:06.866
The thing that influenced her
was watching her family members

00:09:06.866 --> 00:09:07.356
fall apart.

00:09:08.396 --> 00:09:11.846
It was watching her aunt
and uncles become amputees,

00:09:12.386 --> 00:09:15.756
have diabetes, have
diet-related disease,

00:09:15.996 --> 00:09:18.656
have congestive heart
failure, all of these things.

00:09:18.866 --> 00:09:23.906
And I didn't really-- I
didn't put it together

00:09:25.046 --> 00:09:27.836
because I thought
what do you mean?

00:09:27.836 --> 00:09:30.626
I was asking this when I
was I think a young teenager

00:09:30.626 --> 00:09:32.466
so I didn't really
understand the concept

00:09:32.466 --> 00:09:33.496
of diet-related disease.

00:09:33.876 --> 00:09:36.246
I knew what diabetes was and I
knew that it had something to do

00:09:36.246 --> 00:09:38.706
with sugar, but I didn't quiet
understand the correlation

00:09:38.706 --> 00:09:39.556
when it came to food.

00:09:39.846 --> 00:09:42.706
And she said, "Well, you know
Pappy," who was my grandfather.

00:09:43.016 --> 00:09:45.586
"You know how his legs are
wrapped and he can't walk?"

00:09:46.556 --> 00:09:47.186
And I said, "Yeah."

00:09:47.456 --> 00:09:49.446
And she said that's
because of diabetes.

00:09:49.606 --> 00:09:55.006
And I said, "Oh, he-- really?"

00:09:55.346 --> 00:09:55.966
And she said, "Yeah.

00:09:55.966 --> 00:09:56.936
And you know Aunt Mildred?"

00:09:57.126 --> 00:09:58.876
my great aunt, her aunt.

00:09:58.876 --> 00:10:01.326
"You know how she had a
leg amputated last year?"

00:10:02.226 --> 00:10:03.196
And I said, "Yeah."

00:10:03.196 --> 00:10:05.276
And she said, "Well,
that's because of diabetes."

00:10:06.796 --> 00:10:08.256
And she started going
down the list.

00:10:08.936 --> 00:10:09.726
"You know uncle Bate?

00:10:09.726 --> 00:10:12.376
You know how Aunty
Deb has diabetes?

00:10:12.376 --> 00:10:14.626
You know all of these, right,
one right after the other.

00:10:14.626 --> 00:10:18.066
And I'm even getting
emotional talking about it

00:10:18.066 --> 00:10:22.056
like it was my entire
family, my entire family.

00:10:23.176 --> 00:10:25.136
Our immediate family was
some of the only people

00:10:25.136 --> 00:10:27.146
that hadn't been
touched by this.

00:10:27.426 --> 00:10:30.336
And so for her, food was a
way of saving her children.

00:10:31.456 --> 00:10:35.266
It was a way of making sure
that when we had grandchildren,

00:10:35.266 --> 00:10:36.966
when our children
were teenagers,

00:10:37.406 --> 00:10:39.296
they wouldn't lose us.

00:10:39.856 --> 00:10:41.436
So for her, it was justice.

00:10:42.356 --> 00:10:43.586
It was very serious.

00:10:45.026 --> 00:10:47.656
And then I started thinking
about my grandmother,

00:10:47.756 --> 00:10:50.896
and the way that mother
must have grown up.

00:10:51.846 --> 00:10:53.516
When I would go over
my grandmother's house

00:10:53.566 --> 00:10:54.446
when I was little,

00:10:55.276 --> 00:11:00.596
Nana overcooked most
vegetables, right?

00:11:01.026 --> 00:11:02.236
We ate canned beets.

00:11:03.336 --> 00:11:05.126
We ate Kraft mac and cheese.

00:11:05.126 --> 00:11:09.596
One of our snacks, were
those cheese slices, plastic.

00:11:10.856 --> 00:11:13.566
And I thought about how
my mom must have grown

00:11:13.566 --> 00:11:19.236
up eating those 1960s housewife
recipes that were jello was used

00:11:19.236 --> 00:11:22.496
in everything including
meat, kind of disgustingly,

00:11:22.936 --> 00:11:26.376
and the way that she must
have put those dots together.

00:11:26.426 --> 00:11:29.956
And then I started thinking
about the stories I was going

00:11:29.956 --> 00:11:32.666
to tell my children, about
the way that I grew up

00:11:32.666 --> 00:11:33.636
and the food that I ate.

00:11:33.636 --> 00:11:38.366
And it gave me a whole other
level of respect for my family,

00:11:39.526 --> 00:11:47.466
because-- to add complexity
to my food story and the way

00:11:47.466 --> 00:11:51.776
that I grew up, yes, she fed
us macrobiotic food and yes,

00:11:51.866 --> 00:11:53.306
we ate really, really healthy.

00:11:53.556 --> 00:11:59.276
And I didn't know what kale was
until I was 23 years old, right?

00:11:59.936 --> 00:12:02.186
I joined an intentional
community

00:12:02.506 --> 00:12:04.126
because I'm one of those.

00:12:04.126 --> 00:12:05.756
I'm hippy hardcore.

00:12:06.366 --> 00:12:10.206
We had our own chickens.

00:12:10.436 --> 00:12:11.886
We had our garden in the back.

00:12:11.986 --> 00:12:13.126
We had our food cooperative.

00:12:13.126 --> 00:12:15.246
It's in Los Angeles, the
Los Angeles Eco-Village.

00:12:15.246 --> 00:12:16.996
It's 50% people of color.

00:12:17.286 --> 00:12:21.116
It's basically like the most
badass intentional community

00:12:21.476 --> 00:12:22.096
in the country.

00:12:22.526 --> 00:12:25.266
But we would-- started
getting CSA boxes.

00:12:25.266 --> 00:12:28.016
And I had to learn what
these other vegetables were,

00:12:28.116 --> 00:12:31.056
and had to knock on people's
doors every other day.

00:12:31.416 --> 00:12:32.586
What is this?

00:12:33.376 --> 00:12:34.736
How do you cook it?

00:12:34.736 --> 00:12:36.616
And I realized how
much I didn't know.

00:12:36.616 --> 00:12:41.056
As healthy as I thought I was, I
realized how much I didn't know.

00:12:41.056 --> 00:12:42.946
I didn't know beyond
a chain store.

00:12:43.426 --> 00:12:48.406
I didn't know beyond a Ralph's
or Von's or anything like that.

00:12:48.406 --> 00:12:50.416
And then I was the black chick

00:12:50.416 --> 00:12:52.986
in the intentional community
talking about how, you know,

00:12:52.986 --> 00:12:58.196
I eat real good but I don't
know how many varieties

00:12:58.196 --> 00:12:58.936
of apples there are.

00:12:59.806 --> 00:13:00.906
I know delicious red.

00:13:01.786 --> 00:13:03.936
I know that when we had
something to celebrate,

00:13:03.936 --> 00:13:06.566
we went to Sizzler; and
when we really had something

00:13:06.566 --> 00:13:08.556
to celebrate because stuff
that was really good,

00:13:08.556 --> 00:13:09.636
we got to go to Red Lobster.

00:13:09.636 --> 00:13:11.716
That was what I knew.

00:13:12.836 --> 00:13:15.566
And so I had to reconcile the
fact that there were many, many,

00:13:15.566 --> 00:13:19.196
many people like me, who
were on the edge of healthy,

00:13:19.196 --> 00:13:21.756
who ate healthy within
the mainstream context,

00:13:22.266 --> 00:13:24.256
but there was a whole
other layer of healthy

00:13:24.556 --> 00:13:26.966
that I knew nothing about,
that I came to as an adult.

00:13:27.126 --> 00:13:28.996
And it was a very
humbling experience for me,

00:13:29.496 --> 00:13:32.196
because when I thought
about why, I had to go back

00:13:32.196 --> 00:13:34.636
to the context in
which I grew up.

00:13:35.646 --> 00:13:36.766
What I said in the beginning

00:13:36.856 --> 00:13:40.866
about how nonfood factors
usually influence food

00:13:40.866 --> 00:13:44.136
and security, I was an
African-American woman

00:13:44.136 --> 00:13:46.096
who was a child in
the lat 1980s,

00:13:46.096 --> 00:13:54.876
early 1990s in Los Angeles,
California context, right?

00:13:55.536 --> 00:13:58.876
Our first home was on
Wilton Place in 48th.

00:13:58.876 --> 00:14:00.516
And if you know anything
about LA,

00:14:00.716 --> 00:14:04.416
you know that that is smacked
out in the middle of the hood.

00:14:04.416 --> 00:14:06.086
And I remember playing
that game,

00:14:06.326 --> 00:14:08.886
the get down on the ground
game, when you get pops,

00:14:09.436 --> 00:14:12.556
and I didn't know that it
wasn't a game when I was little.

00:14:12.556 --> 00:14:15.306
I just knew that my parents
tried to make something

00:14:15.306 --> 00:14:18.896
like a drive-by shooting,
not be terrifying for me.

00:14:20.496 --> 00:14:21.686
I remember the LA riots.

00:14:21.856 --> 00:14:24.946
I remember crashes and things
burning, and not outside

00:14:24.946 --> 00:14:27.446
of our door but I
remember my friend coming

00:14:27.446 --> 00:14:29.996
over with lots of stuff, right?

00:14:29.996 --> 00:14:31.316
Where'd you get all that stuff?

00:14:31.316 --> 00:14:33.426
We got it from stores and
if there was something going

00:14:33.426 --> 00:14:34.566
on that I didn't know about,

00:14:35.086 --> 00:14:37.496
something outside,
something on the TV.

00:14:37.496 --> 00:14:40.216
There was a reason why my mom
was crying, I didn't know why.

00:14:41.796 --> 00:14:46.296
If any of you-- the
context in the early '90s

00:14:46.296 --> 00:14:47.406
that most people
have for that is

00:14:47.406 --> 00:14:50.286
that is Menace II
Society, Boyz on the Hood.

00:14:50.676 --> 00:14:53.946
Statistically, the gang
wars in Los Angeles during

00:14:53.946 --> 00:14:57.006
that period are one of the most
vicious civil wars America has

00:14:57.006 --> 00:15:02.176
had, 15,000 young men and
women were killed within a four

00:15:02.176 --> 00:15:06.206
to five year period
in that time, 15,000.

00:15:06.546 --> 00:15:09.286
And I have brothers.

00:15:09.426 --> 00:15:11.356
I have older foster brothers.

00:15:11.356 --> 00:15:13.886
I have younger blood brothers.

00:15:14.786 --> 00:15:18.866
So for my parents raising
black children in Los Angeles

00:15:18.906 --> 00:15:22.826
in the late '80s, early
'90s was no fucking joke.

00:15:24.216 --> 00:15:29.646
For us to be healthy, for us to
be safe, they had to do a lot.

00:15:30.766 --> 00:15:32.396
They had to shield
us from a lot.

00:15:33.606 --> 00:15:36.326
They had to figure out what
they were going to do for work.

00:15:36.396 --> 00:15:39.316
What we were going to do for
play that was going to make sure

00:15:39.316 --> 00:15:41.956
that we didn't grow up thinking

00:15:41.956 --> 00:15:44.126
that the only thing our people
could is kill each other.

00:15:44.186 --> 00:15:50.346
And food was one of the
ways that they kept us safe.

00:15:50.376 --> 00:15:51.936
So it's so much more
important to me

00:15:51.936 --> 00:15:53.666
than just my mom
wanted to eat healthy.

00:15:54.306 --> 00:16:00.686
And when we think about
that on a larger scale,

00:16:00.686 --> 00:16:04.656
there was a study done
called "Unnatural Causes:

00:16:04.866 --> 00:16:06.766
Is Inequality Making Us Sick?"

00:16:06.876 --> 00:16:10.536
And this was a study that
was turned into a movie.

00:16:10.536 --> 00:16:12.676
You can look at out there
clips of it on YouTube

00:16:13.056 --> 00:16:14.776
about the social
determinance of health.

00:16:15.466 --> 00:16:17.256
Food is just one of them.

00:16:18.196 --> 00:16:22.296
But one of the things, there
were startling statistics

00:16:22.296 --> 00:16:23.576
that they did these
vignettes on.

00:16:23.766 --> 00:16:24.886
And one of the one that stood

00:16:24.886 --> 00:16:27.756
out to me always was the
infant mortality section.

00:16:29.036 --> 00:16:32.066
Because statistically,
a white woman in America

00:16:32.066 --> 00:16:34.856
with a high school diploma has
a lower infant mortality rate

00:16:34.856 --> 00:16:38.816
than an African-American
woman with a PhD today.

00:16:39.996 --> 00:16:41.526
That was startling to me.

00:16:42.216 --> 00:16:46.216
And the reason why is
very uncomfortable,

00:16:47.426 --> 00:16:50.946
because when you look at it
historically, African-Americans

00:16:50.946 --> 00:16:55.966
in America, middle class and
upper class African-Americans,

00:16:55.966 --> 00:16:57.796
very, very, very
small percentage

00:16:57.796 --> 00:17:00.106
of African-American
had grandparents

00:17:00.106 --> 00:17:02.556
that were brain surgeons,
and things like that.

00:17:02.916 --> 00:17:07.236
Usually, you become middle class
through hard work yourself,

00:17:07.396 --> 00:17:09.376
and that you get a good job

00:17:09.696 --> 00:17:11.906
and you become middle
class when you're an adult.

00:17:11.906 --> 00:17:16.246
But during your formative
years from 0 to 5 and 5 to 10,

00:17:16.816 --> 00:17:18.466
you're still breathing
the same air

00:17:18.466 --> 00:17:20.506
that working class people are.

00:17:21.606 --> 00:17:25.826
Your system is still getting
triggered, constantly triggered

00:17:26.296 --> 00:17:29.606
by the unknown, by
survival mode, by violence.

00:17:29.786 --> 00:17:33.366
And this is when your
reproductive system is forming.

00:17:33.646 --> 00:17:35.946
And it never goes away.

00:17:37.526 --> 00:17:38.756
It's cumulative.

00:17:39.756 --> 00:17:42.806
The effects of poverty
are cumulative.

00:17:43.126 --> 00:17:45.346
And that was one of the
most important things

00:17:45.346 --> 00:17:46.596
that this study emphasized.

00:17:47.196 --> 00:17:52.616
You can't get out because
if you were there at all,

00:17:53.086 --> 00:17:54.026
it stays in your body.

00:17:55.216 --> 00:17:59.206
I will have a lower infant
mortality rate because of some

00:17:59.206 --> 00:18:02.476
of the things I went through as
a young child and someone else

00:18:02.616 --> 00:18:05.126
who didn't grow up like me,
no matter where I end up.

00:18:05.126 --> 00:18:07.706
And that's really humbling.

00:18:08.826 --> 00:18:13.126
So when we talk about justice,
we are actually talking

00:18:13.126 --> 00:18:15.816
about everyone, from
beginning to end.

00:18:17.146 --> 00:18:20.706
And there's always food deserts
to go along with these things.

00:18:20.796 --> 00:18:22.676
That's just infant
mortality when it comes

00:18:22.676 --> 00:18:24.506
to the stress hormone
running through our bodies,

00:18:24.936 --> 00:18:26.216
when it comes to air and water.

00:18:27.556 --> 00:18:31.276
But any community dealing
with the social determinance

00:18:31.276 --> 00:18:32.856
of health, where
there is poverty,

00:18:33.166 --> 00:18:34.456
there are also liquor stores.

00:18:35.866 --> 00:18:42.276
And this is a really good
time to share some hope

00:18:43.606 --> 00:18:50.276
because there's a lot of tension
around this kind of thing.

00:18:50.276 --> 00:18:52.756
And one of things that was
really hopeful to me is

00:18:52.756 --> 00:18:56.306
that people with color
and those most impacted

00:18:56.306 --> 00:18:58.046
by an issue, are brilliant.

00:18:59.166 --> 00:19:02.726
In terms of mother being the--

00:19:03.416 --> 00:19:06.946
need being the source of
all invention, we will come

00:19:06.946 --> 00:19:09.096
up with things and we
will figure it out.

00:19:09.096 --> 00:19:12.446
I was the executive director
of People's Grocery in Oakland,

00:19:12.446 --> 00:19:16.106
California for many years,
and one of the main programs

00:19:16.106 --> 00:19:18.146
that we had was the
Growing Justice Institute.

00:19:18.516 --> 00:19:19.726
Now, one of the impetuous

00:19:19.726 --> 00:19:22.966
for the Growing Justice
Institute was we wanted young

00:19:22.966 --> 00:19:28.026
people to be able get
jobs, to get good training,

00:19:28.026 --> 00:19:29.896
to go out there and really
do their thing, right?

00:19:30.216 --> 00:19:33.116
But then when we had discussions
at the office, we thought,

00:19:33.156 --> 00:19:37.906
"Well, do we want to just train
them to get low-paying jobs

00:19:37.986 --> 00:19:40.056
because 7 of the 10
lowest paying jobs

00:19:40.056 --> 00:19:41.176
in the country are food jobs?"

00:19:41.366 --> 00:19:43.616
So that's probably
not going to work.

00:19:44.436 --> 00:19:47.556
We don't want to train them
into $2.15 minimum wage

00:19:47.556 --> 00:19:48.416
as a server somewhere.

00:19:49.286 --> 00:19:52.406
So, we thought this needs to
be an entrepreneurship program.

00:19:52.406 --> 00:19:55.766
And let's start with adults
because once we have adults

00:19:55.766 --> 00:19:58.366
who were going to the program,
well, we can transition this

00:19:58.446 --> 00:20:00.606
to really being a functional
healthy youth program.

00:20:00.606 --> 00:20:04.346
And when we got this
group of people,

00:20:04.546 --> 00:20:08.076
it was nine African-American
adults from West Oakland.

00:20:08.216 --> 00:20:13.056
And we said, "What solutions do
you have for the problem of food

00:20:13.056 --> 00:20:14.436
in security in West Oakland?"

00:20:14.856 --> 00:20:19.046
The stuff they come up with
was freaking brilliant,

00:20:20.386 --> 00:20:23.816
absolutely brilliant, right?

00:20:24.276 --> 00:20:26.526
We had a partnership
with Highland Hospital

00:20:26.886 --> 00:20:28.746
which was the public
hospital in Oakland.

00:20:28.746 --> 00:20:32.286
And we were doing a childhood
obesity case study, right?

00:20:32.336 --> 00:20:35.036
So there was the
pediatric obesity clinic,

00:20:35.466 --> 00:20:39.446
and all these two and
three-year-olds who had diabetes

00:20:39.996 --> 00:20:42.216
and diet-related
disease and were obese,

00:20:43.076 --> 00:20:44.906
because now two-year-olds
can be obese.

00:20:45.526 --> 00:20:48.196
And so, they partnered
with us to give each

00:20:48.196 --> 00:20:50.796
of these families a community
supported agriculture box

00:20:51.336 --> 00:20:54.446
and cooking lessons and recipes,
and have a support group,

00:20:54.716 --> 00:20:56.726
around incorporating
healthy food into their diet.

00:20:56.726 --> 00:21:00.466
And actually, a quick
vignette about this program

00:21:00.466 --> 00:21:02.576
because this is also
the ingenuity of people.

00:21:02.866 --> 00:21:06.546
This is a primarily Latino group
and so we had a translator.

00:21:06.546 --> 00:21:09.266
And one of the beautiful
things that happened with it,

00:21:09.266 --> 00:21:12.646
we tried to do the regular
cooking class recipes,

00:21:12.936 --> 00:21:14.706
what do you eat at
home conversation.

00:21:15.096 --> 00:21:17.426
And then just said, let's just
get these people in a circle

00:21:17.426 --> 00:21:18.626
and have them talk
to each other.

00:21:18.996 --> 00:21:21.146
And the stuff that
happened was incredible.

00:21:22.026 --> 00:21:23.996
There were conversations
about, hey,

00:21:23.996 --> 00:21:25.566
you can put these
things in tamales.

00:21:25.566 --> 00:21:28.056
I tried it last night,
it worked, right?

00:21:28.436 --> 00:21:30.596
And this is how I got
my kids to eat it.

00:21:30.986 --> 00:21:33.766
Hey, I'd chop this up and put
the spice on it and put it

00:21:33.766 --> 00:21:36.346
in a tostada, they didn't
know the difference.

00:21:36.376 --> 00:21:38.956
And they were just--
it was just hilarious

00:21:38.956 --> 00:21:41.146
about all these parents
who are fooling their kids

00:21:41.406 --> 00:21:44.236
in eating these different foods
and it was actually working.

00:21:45.026 --> 00:21:46.146
It was actually working.

00:21:46.686 --> 00:21:51.646
And so, one note that I just
want to throw in there is

00:21:51.646 --> 00:21:54.056
that creativity will find a way.

00:21:55.016 --> 00:21:59.256
It will find a way but you have
to give it space to breathe

00:21:59.656 --> 00:22:01.616
and leave it alone, so one

00:22:01.616 --> 00:22:03.366
of the Growing Justice
Institute people wanted

00:22:03.366 --> 00:22:04.466
to be a nutrition educator.

00:22:05.146 --> 00:22:08.456
And so, we sent her to
this hospital project

00:22:09.006 --> 00:22:11.116
as our representative to
do the nutrition classes.

00:22:11.116 --> 00:22:12.606
And it was one of
her first contracts.

00:22:12.606 --> 00:22:14.506
And now, she runs a very
successful nutrition

00:22:14.506 --> 00:22:15.316
consulting business.

00:22:16.236 --> 00:22:18.656
There was another woman who
did a partnership with a church

00:22:19.546 --> 00:22:21.716
where she put a garden at
the church so that the food

00:22:21.716 --> 00:22:23.736
that was being served on
Sundays could be sourced

00:22:23.736 --> 00:22:24.266
from the garden.

00:22:24.266 --> 00:22:28.096
And there are programs like this
that exist all over the country.

00:22:28.256 --> 00:22:30.116
But usually, when I
see programs like that,

00:22:30.116 --> 00:22:33.496
they're run by a nonprofit
and funded by a foundation.

00:22:33.926 --> 00:22:36.226
They're not run by the people
in the community who came

00:22:36.226 --> 00:22:38.216
up with the idea who
maybe got a microgrant

00:22:38.216 --> 00:22:40.266
and are doing an
independent of anybody else.

00:22:41.126 --> 00:22:44.646
There was a woman who lived in
a housing project who noticed

00:22:44.676 --> 00:22:48.036
that there were source--
there were resources for them

00:22:48.036 --> 00:22:50.906
to get healthy food but
people couldn't get there.

00:22:51.186 --> 00:22:53.146
So she organized a
transportation service

00:22:53.146 --> 00:22:56.286
to specifically go to a farmer's
market, go to the wick office,

00:22:56.286 --> 00:22:57.846
and go to different places

00:22:57.846 --> 00:23:00.516
where there were food
resources, a van service.

00:23:00.646 --> 00:23:04.426
And every single project
was just as applicable,

00:23:05.356 --> 00:23:07.806
every single project, brilliant.

00:23:07.806 --> 00:23:09.276
We actually didn't
have to do that much.

00:23:09.906 --> 00:23:12.966
And so one thing I want to
emphasize when we're talking

00:23:12.966 --> 00:23:16.916
about creating justice is that
there are real-time examples

00:23:17.306 --> 00:23:19.906
of what it means to
give people the space

00:23:19.976 --> 00:23:22.866
to develop their own ideas
and give them the support

00:23:22.866 --> 00:23:25.586
that it takes to make sure
that they can do it themselves.

00:23:26.666 --> 00:23:28.656
But then, this leads
us to attention.

00:23:29.696 --> 00:23:32.216
Because when we're talking
about the bigger picture

00:23:32.216 --> 00:23:35.516
of food security, there
are a lot of complexities.

00:23:36.576 --> 00:23:40.876
One of the complexities
is the way that we talk

00:23:40.876 --> 00:23:46.046
about healthy food and
what is healthy in America.

00:23:46.976 --> 00:23:49.406
MyPlate, right?

00:23:49.586 --> 00:23:52.976
MyPlate. I still really can't
deal with MyPlate because I grew

00:23:52.976 --> 00:23:55.096
up with a food pyramid
and that's always going

00:23:55.096 --> 00:23:57.996
to be the image that is emblazed
in my head because Nana had

00:23:57.996 --> 00:23:59.706
that on the cabinet
next to the refrigerator

00:24:00.276 --> 00:24:02.186
but MyPlate is the same idea.

00:24:03.486 --> 00:24:06.156
And we used to have
food journals

00:24:06.436 --> 00:24:07.756
at People's Grocery as well.

00:24:07.756 --> 00:24:10.056
And we had many different
types of people

00:24:10.056 --> 00:24:11.276
from many different cultures

00:24:11.806 --> 00:24:13.876
who are recording their
daily intake of food.

00:24:14.256 --> 00:24:16.506
And when we were trying to
encourage them to eat healthy

00:24:16.506 --> 00:24:18.386
and they wanted recommendations,
we would say, well,

00:24:18.386 --> 00:24:20.956
you can eat this, this,
this, this and that.

00:24:20.956 --> 00:24:22.666
And these foods are healthy.

00:24:23.856 --> 00:24:27.906
But something that is very
uncomfortable to talk about is

00:24:27.906 --> 00:24:29.886
that actually people

00:24:29.886 --> 00:24:32.246
with different ethnicities
do have some

00:24:32.316 --> 00:24:33.276
biological differences.

00:24:33.906 --> 00:24:39.096
We have different food
sensitivities depending

00:24:39.096 --> 00:24:41.286
on where we come from, right?

00:24:41.876 --> 00:24:44.126
Something that I can
eat might make you sick.

00:24:44.126 --> 00:24:47.136
And with there might be
some similarities in terms

00:24:47.136 --> 00:24:49.226
of your ethnic group and
your cultural background

00:24:49.606 --> 00:24:51.526
with the types of food
sensitivities you have.

00:24:52.246 --> 00:24:55.476
And we discovered this
pretty organically, right?

00:24:56.006 --> 00:24:58.216
There are certain people,
especially people that come

00:24:58.216 --> 00:25:00.386
from cultures that have been
in the same place for thousands

00:25:00.386 --> 00:25:01.866
of years and have an intermix.

00:25:01.936 --> 00:25:04.106
I'm a hodgepodge because
I'm a child of slavery.

00:25:04.146 --> 00:25:07.316
So I can-- you know, I have a
little bit of food sensitivity

00:25:07.316 --> 00:25:08.366
to almost everything,

00:25:08.366 --> 00:25:10.496
but my body can also
process almost everything.

00:25:10.696 --> 00:25:12.356
Because I got the masses' blood,

00:25:12.356 --> 00:25:13.986
I got the Cherokee
folks that own me.

00:25:13.986 --> 00:25:16.176
I got their blood, yeah,
all of that, that's all me.

00:25:16.736 --> 00:25:18.476
So I feel pretty
lucky in the game.

00:25:18.476 --> 00:25:19.866
But there were a lot
of people who came

00:25:19.866 --> 00:25:21.126
through People's
Grocery's doors.

00:25:21.546 --> 00:25:22.446
Who kept saying, you know,

00:25:22.446 --> 00:25:25.356
I'm trying to eat what my
doctor is telling me to eat,

00:25:25.726 --> 00:25:26.996
and it's making me sick.

00:25:28.186 --> 00:25:30.626
And so, we had to take them
to the process as saying, OK,

00:25:30.626 --> 00:25:31.816
what did your grandmother eat?

00:25:31.816 --> 00:25:33.976
Do you remember?

00:25:33.976 --> 00:25:35.456
Do you remember the recipes?

00:25:35.456 --> 00:25:36.936
Do you remember the
spices that they used?

00:25:37.306 --> 00:25:38.326
Most specifically,

00:25:38.326 --> 00:25:41.516
do you remember the food
combinations that they did?

00:25:41.626 --> 00:25:44.176
Because I will not tell you how
many times I have gone to one

00:25:44.176 --> 00:25:45.676
of these damn foodie restaurants

00:25:46.016 --> 00:25:47.636
that are mixing all
these different types

00:25:47.636 --> 00:25:50.756
of foods together and mashing
this up and using this spice.

00:25:50.756 --> 00:25:53.486
And then I have gas
and I'm sick afterward.

00:25:53.766 --> 00:25:56.106
And it's like, yeah, these food
combinations have not existed

00:25:56.106 --> 00:25:56.966
for thousands of years,

00:25:57.196 --> 00:25:59.576
but there are food combinations
that really do work.

00:25:59.576 --> 00:26:01.196
So don't just start
mixing things together,

00:26:01.196 --> 00:26:02.236
thinking that it's
going to work.

00:26:02.606 --> 00:26:04.206
And 9 times out of 10,

00:26:04.636 --> 00:26:07.286
when these people started eating
what their grandmother's ate,

00:26:08.156 --> 00:26:08.736
they got better.

00:26:09.286 --> 00:26:11.696
It didn't always work
and it wasn't that linear

00:26:12.206 --> 00:26:14.626
but there was a theme
there that we saw.

00:26:14.626 --> 00:26:18.546
And so, the implications for
trying to do food planning

00:26:19.326 --> 00:26:22.466
and food systems
development in America is

00:26:22.466 --> 00:26:26.576
that MyPlate is not going to
work for everyone, it's not.

00:26:27.866 --> 00:26:31.136
And when we talk about places
that don't have grocery stores,

00:26:31.186 --> 00:26:33.356
the only kind of grocery
stores that are funded

00:26:33.356 --> 00:26:36.326
by the $200 million fresh food
initiative and things like that,

00:26:37.326 --> 00:26:38.746
are mainstream grocery stores.

00:26:39.516 --> 00:26:42.126
They're not ethnic
markets, typically.

00:26:42.676 --> 00:26:46.326
But we have got to start
grouping ethnic markets

00:26:46.326 --> 00:26:48.656
into the bigger picture when
we talk about groceries.

00:26:49.986 --> 00:26:54.536
Korean markets, African markets,
the Mexican markets that are

00:26:54.536 --> 00:26:55.776
in Southern California.

00:26:55.776 --> 00:26:58.646
The Guatemalan markets,
they're in Southern California.

00:26:58.946 --> 00:27:00.236
All these different
types of markets

00:27:00.276 --> 00:27:02.886
that will sell foods
the different types

00:27:02.886 --> 00:27:05.696
of people can eat is a
very, very important factor.

00:27:05.766 --> 00:27:08.426
And we need to figure out,
how to have that conversation,

00:27:09.796 --> 00:27:12.926
which leads to a much deeper
issue and a much deeper tension

00:27:13.386 --> 00:27:16.606
when we're talking about
food security which is--

00:27:18.436 --> 00:27:21.686
you know what, I can
see that the energy

00:27:21.686 --> 00:27:22.776
in the room has dampened.

00:27:22.776 --> 00:27:24.166
It's hard to sit and
listen to someone

00:27:24.166 --> 00:27:25.426
for a long period
of time, I know.

00:27:25.736 --> 00:27:28.306
Everybody stand up.

00:27:28.606 --> 00:27:30.976
We're going to do an energizer

00:27:30.976 --> 00:27:34.176
because our bodies
need [inaudible].

00:27:35.186 --> 00:27:36.676
Everybody lift your hands up.

00:27:36.986 --> 00:27:37.406
Wiggle your fingers.

00:27:37.406 --> 00:27:41.046
Stretch it out a
