Shake it out.

00:28:13.106 --> 00:28:16.566
All right, sit back down.

00:28:16.566 --> 00:28:17.056
Good job.

00:28:23.736 --> 00:28:28.246
So, now that we're back.

00:28:28.726 --> 00:28:33.046
Another tension and we're going

00:28:33.046 --> 00:28:35.766
to get a little bit
political right now.

00:28:36.266 --> 00:28:39.096
So come with me, it's OK.

00:28:40.026 --> 00:28:44.386
But this whole thing about
patenting seeds, right?

00:28:44.386 --> 00:28:52.906
When you're dealing with ethnic
cultures who have had thousands

00:28:52.906 --> 00:28:56.826
of years of food
traditions, doing something

00:28:56.826 --> 00:29:02.346
like commodifying the DNA
and the genetic profile

00:29:02.346 --> 00:29:05.236
of their seeds is
culture-destroying.

00:29:06.816 --> 00:29:09.666
And unfortunately, a lot
of economic development

00:29:09.666 --> 00:29:12.606
and culture destruction
go hand and hand.

00:29:13.236 --> 00:29:14.136
That's just the way

00:29:14.136 --> 00:29:16.776
that globalization
imperialism has worked

00:29:17.146 --> 00:29:18.546
over the last few hundred years.

00:29:18.626 --> 00:29:23.236
But the implication for our
food system has gotten really,

00:29:23.236 --> 00:29:25.706
really intense especially
recently.

00:29:27.336 --> 00:29:32.926
Because one of the most--
going back to climate change,

00:29:33.176 --> 00:29:35.876
one of the first ways
that people in America

00:29:35.876 --> 00:29:38.166
and worldwide are going
to experience the effects

00:29:38.166 --> 00:29:42.286
of climate change is through
food, because minor fluctuations

00:29:42.286 --> 00:29:44.866
in temperature will
dramatically effect crops.

00:29:45.706 --> 00:29:48.846
And that will lead to spikes
in the price of grains

00:29:48.846 --> 00:29:52.606
which is a huge subsistence crop
for the majority of the world.

00:29:53.576 --> 00:29:57.186
And that leads to food rights,
as we've seen on and off

00:29:57.186 --> 00:29:58.306
over the last 10 years.

00:29:58.996 --> 00:30:01.646
But when you go a
step underneath that,

00:30:02.406 --> 00:30:04.316
what you're looking
at is the way

00:30:04.316 --> 00:30:06.886
that when people have their food
traditions taken away from them,

00:30:06.886 --> 00:30:08.526
it's a huge blow
to their culture.

00:30:09.926 --> 00:30:11.766
And when you commodify food,

00:30:11.766 --> 00:30:16.296
you're destroying
a piece of people.

00:30:16.856 --> 00:30:20.026
So, how do you interact
with that?

00:30:21.016 --> 00:30:23.066
Not all commodification
of food is bad.

00:30:23.336 --> 00:30:24.296
There's always been trade.

00:30:24.296 --> 00:30:25.186
There's always been barter.

00:30:25.186 --> 00:30:27.086
There's always been the
buying and selling of things.

00:30:27.536 --> 00:30:31.376
What I'm talking about is scale
of which this is happening,

00:30:31.376 --> 00:30:36.246
and the balance, and trying to
make sure that we do it in a way

00:30:36.626 --> 00:30:40.276
that preserves cultures
while still ensuring

00:30:40.276 --> 00:30:42.156
that there is enough
economic development

00:30:42.156 --> 00:30:44.316
so that everyone has
their basic needs met.

00:30:45.296 --> 00:30:48.246
The unfortunate thing about
this larger conversation is just

00:30:48.246 --> 00:30:50.086
that most of the time;
there isn't a conversation

00:30:50.086 --> 00:30:53.366
about balance, because
culture is not preserved

00:30:53.676 --> 00:30:56.256
at the same rate as the
basic need is preserved.

00:30:57.556 --> 00:31:00.666
Or culture isn't
preserved at the rate

00:31:00.846 --> 00:31:02.176
that economic development

00:31:02.226 --> 00:31:04.736
to meet everyone's basic
needs is increasing.

00:31:05.726 --> 00:31:07.116
I'll say that.

00:31:07.396 --> 00:31:10.136
But there is even
opportunity in that.

00:31:10.686 --> 00:31:13.316
Because the raw ingredients
for the food movement

00:31:14.316 --> 00:31:18.846
to become a force, to
become a real force;

00:31:19.546 --> 00:31:24.336
the way that other movements
are and happen, I don't know

00:31:24.336 --> 00:31:28.006
that I've seen any better
raw ingredients especially

00:31:28.006 --> 00:31:30.056
when you look at
social movement theory.

00:31:30.256 --> 00:31:31.886
What I just said
about climate change

00:31:31.886 --> 00:31:36.076
in food is actually pretty
significant, because the amount

00:31:36.076 --> 00:31:38.456
of money right now that
is being rerouted to deal

00:31:38.456 --> 00:31:42.246
with the climate crisis
is enormous, enormous.

00:31:42.996 --> 00:31:47.426
The president's resiliency task
force last year was 25 mayors

00:31:47.826 --> 00:31:49.936
from all across the country
that were coming together

00:31:50.196 --> 00:31:52.906
to support the president with
recommendations about how

00:31:52.906 --> 00:31:56.056
to make cities across the
country more climate resilient

00:31:56.056 --> 00:31:58.566
when there's cases
of extreme weather.

00:31:58.566 --> 00:32:01.206
And these recommendations
are going to translate

00:32:01.206 --> 00:32:04.266
into every single department in
the United States government,

00:32:04.266 --> 00:32:06.106
rerouting a certain
part of their budget

00:32:06.366 --> 00:32:07.686
to climate resiliency.

00:32:08.676 --> 00:32:11.796
And if food is one of the first
ways that people are going

00:32:11.796 --> 00:32:13.466
to interact with climate change,

00:32:14.846 --> 00:32:17.126
that means that our
movement just got access

00:32:17.186 --> 00:32:18.816
to millions of dollars.

00:32:20.376 --> 00:32:26.836
But we're not really talking
about it that way yet.

00:32:26.836 --> 00:32:30.586
Now, when it comes to a
national movement that's founded

00:32:30.586 --> 00:32:33.626
in justice, the food
movement also has

00:32:33.626 --> 00:32:34.756
to leg up another movement.

00:32:36.236 --> 00:32:38.046
When you look at the
environmental movement,

00:32:38.576 --> 00:32:44.196
it was really-- there's
a funny conversation

00:32:44.196 --> 00:32:46.756
that I've been having with
the big green groups in DC

00:32:46.756 --> 00:32:49.396
because the environmental
movement has stopped being

00:32:49.496 --> 00:32:52.836
scary, and so it's
losing a bit of steam.

00:32:54.336 --> 00:32:57.566
But, I mean, they were
kidnapping people in the 1970s.

00:32:57.566 --> 00:32:58.926
When I read about
what was happening

00:32:58.926 --> 00:33:04.736
to get the Clean Air Act
and Clean Water Act passed,

00:33:05.566 --> 00:33:06.786
they were-- they were some--
they were [inaudible].

00:33:06.786 --> 00:33:08.386
You know, they weren't
the immediate we're going

00:33:08.386 --> 00:33:10.836
to go become a party
establishment kind of folks,

00:33:10.836 --> 00:33:12.746
or at least they were
the establishment folks.

00:33:12.746 --> 00:33:14.806
They had their lawyers but
they also had the people

00:33:14.806 --> 00:33:19.826
that were willing to, you
know, burn things, splash paint

00:33:19.826 --> 00:33:23.306
on things and be really
scary; and those parts

00:33:23.306 --> 00:33:26.086
of the environmental movement
have all gradually been sucked

00:33:26.086 --> 00:33:27.196
into the bigger machine,

00:33:27.516 --> 00:33:29.646
and then we wonder why we can't
pass the climate bill, right.

00:33:29.976 --> 00:33:32.286
Part of social movement
theory is that you have

00:33:32.316 --> 00:33:35.856
to have the people that are
super scary to make the people

00:33:35.856 --> 00:33:38.956
who were trying to
actually be balanced look

00:33:38.956 --> 00:33:41.146
at a lot more attractive
to the powers they'd be.

00:33:41.856 --> 00:33:43.716
The scary people have to exist.

00:33:43.816 --> 00:33:47.426
And in food, we actually
have a bunch of people

00:33:47.426 --> 00:33:48.326
who were in the middle.

00:33:49.346 --> 00:33:51.076
We have a lot of people
who were in the middle,

00:33:51.226 --> 00:33:52.906
who could pretty
easily come over and be

00:33:52.906 --> 00:33:55.946
in the establishment,
and who was, you know,

00:33:56.366 --> 00:34:00.426
one or two more years could be
over here just chaining herself

00:34:00.426 --> 00:34:04.856
to things everyday, right?

00:34:05.486 --> 00:34:08.946
And the opportunity
in that is enormous.

00:34:09.896 --> 00:34:13.616
Because when we sophisticate as
a movement, and we really start

00:34:13.616 --> 00:34:16.796
to talk strategy in a different
way, we're going to be able

00:34:16.796 --> 00:34:20.936
to have the full spectrum of
pressure and the full spectrum

00:34:20.936 --> 00:34:22.376
of what it takes to build power.

00:34:23.896 --> 00:34:26.836
And we are naturally moving
forward in that momentum.

00:34:27.456 --> 00:34:28.746
And more importantly,

00:34:29.006 --> 00:34:33.006
the mainstream food movement
doesn't exist the same way

00:34:33.006 --> 00:34:35.086
that the mainstream
environmental movement does.

00:34:35.516 --> 00:34:39.016
There aren't huge cadres of
people of color trying to break

00:34:39.016 --> 00:34:41.256
into the mainstream
food movement,

00:34:42.106 --> 00:34:44.496
because food justice is
actually pretty mainstream

00:34:44.706 --> 00:34:47.776
which is pretty surprising but
not surprising when you think

00:34:47.776 --> 00:34:50.016
about the fact that the First
Lady is an African American

00:34:50.016 --> 00:34:51.726
woman, and the Let's
Move campaign is one

00:34:51.726 --> 00:34:54.446
of the most mainstream
things you have.

00:34:54.446 --> 00:34:55.976
The understanding that children

00:34:55.976 --> 00:34:59.046
of color are the most food
insecure people in this country

00:34:59.046 --> 00:35:01.686
because they come from single
black mamas is a thing.

00:35:01.686 --> 00:35:02.796
It's a thing in DC.

00:35:02.936 --> 00:35:04.626
It's a thing in Hollywood.

00:35:04.806 --> 00:35:06.096
It's a thing on the streets.

00:35:06.456 --> 00:35:09.126
There have been very
few movements

00:35:09.536 --> 00:35:12.786
that have had the potential
to be founded in justice.

00:35:13.546 --> 00:35:17.686
I just want that to
sit for a second.

00:35:18.476 --> 00:35:21.056
When we really start
to feel ourselves,

00:35:21.056 --> 00:35:24.816
and when we really see
ourselves as what we can be,

00:35:25.356 --> 00:35:28.266
there hasn't really
been a movement like us,

00:35:28.626 --> 00:35:31.506
and it's important for that
to just be internalized.

00:35:33.916 --> 00:35:35.216
So what can you do?

00:35:35.896 --> 00:35:42.256
So a lot of information and
I've been talking quite a bit.

00:35:42.446 --> 00:35:43.786
How does this get personalized?

00:35:44.316 --> 00:35:50.196
One thing that's really
important to remember is

00:35:50.326 --> 00:35:55.276
to locate yourself in
the fight for justice.

00:35:56.736 --> 00:35:57.566
Who are you?

00:35:58.186 --> 00:36:00.996
Who are your people
and what is your fight?

00:36:02.646 --> 00:36:06.056
And allow yourself to be
surprised by the answer.

00:36:07.386 --> 00:36:10.716
One secret that I have
kind of carried for a lot

00:36:10.716 --> 00:36:15.566
of my life is the fact that
when I think about food,

00:36:16.416 --> 00:36:18.996
what gets me emotional
in terms of the people

00:36:18.996 --> 00:36:20.866
that don't have anyone
to speak for them,

00:36:21.646 --> 00:36:25.516
are white Midwesterners who
have nothing but strip malls

00:36:26.286 --> 00:36:33.156
and are morbidly obese, who
are on the political scale,

00:36:34.176 --> 00:36:36.126
much close to Sarah
Palin than Obama.

00:36:36.696 --> 00:36:40.086
It surprises the hell out of me.

00:36:40.216 --> 00:36:41.446
I'll tell you that much.

00:36:41.636 --> 00:36:43.986
I didn't grow up with
these people, right?

00:36:44.276 --> 00:36:45.356
Working class white people

00:36:45.356 --> 00:36:47.066
in Los Angeles actually
don't exist.

00:36:47.066 --> 00:36:48.316
They get pushed out
to the suburbs.

00:36:48.946 --> 00:36:50.686
But now, my husband
is a white man

00:36:50.686 --> 00:36:52.486
and I have an uncle in Texas.

00:36:53.566 --> 00:36:59.246
And there has been this, there
has been this realization

00:36:59.246 --> 00:37:01.996
and this understanding
in me that the part of me

00:37:02.576 --> 00:37:05.206
that felt compassion and
that felt drawn to fight

00:37:05.206 --> 00:37:07.656
for that community was the
part of me that recognizes

00:37:08.566 --> 00:37:12.466
that people that are supposed
to fight for everyone, liberals,

00:37:12.856 --> 00:37:20.156
progressives, democrats,
make fun of them.

00:37:20.366 --> 00:37:24.066
We can be really
mean, progressives.

00:37:24.836 --> 00:37:27.606
We can alienate.

00:37:27.686 --> 00:37:28.526
We can ridicule.

00:37:28.526 --> 00:37:29.236
We can mock.

00:37:31.276 --> 00:37:34.826
And yeah, a lot of those
people are fighting for things

00:37:34.826 --> 00:37:35.786
that we don't believe in,

00:37:37.026 --> 00:37:40.426
but most working
class white Americans

00:37:40.426 --> 00:37:45.646
in this country are just
being manipulated by news,

00:37:46.336 --> 00:37:49.466
by the actual 1% that
doesn't want things to change.

00:37:50.166 --> 00:37:51.926
There are actually
plenty of people in the 1%

00:37:51.926 --> 00:37:53.096
who do want things to change.

00:37:53.416 --> 00:37:56.856
But there's a whole machine
that pits us against each other,

00:37:56.946 --> 00:37:58.926
that has for a very long time.

00:37:59.796 --> 00:38:01.436
And some part of me
saw through that.

00:38:02.146 --> 00:38:06.756
So when I say locate yourself in
the fight for justice, I mean,

00:38:06.756 --> 00:38:09.886
who are your people for real?

00:38:14.116 --> 00:38:16.456
I also want to note
that we need to be clear

00:38:16.936 --> 00:38:18.246
when it comes to ideology.

00:38:18.766 --> 00:38:20.766
That's also something
that we can do.

00:38:21.686 --> 00:38:23.136
One of the most horrifying
things

00:38:23.136 --> 00:38:24.846
that I encountered this
year was coal piling.

00:38:25.246 --> 00:38:27.386
Do people know what
coal piling is?

00:38:28.236 --> 00:38:30.606
Getting a lot-- OK,
so coal piling is

00:38:30.606 --> 00:38:34.316
when you have a big ass
truck, gas dazzling truck,

00:38:34.836 --> 00:38:38.066
and you put a smoke stack
type thing on the back of it

00:38:38.416 --> 00:38:41.676
to deliberately blow black smoke
when you're driving in front

00:38:41.676 --> 00:38:48.746
of a Prius just to say FU in
your environmentalism, right?

00:38:49.186 --> 00:38:50.746
So this is a thing.

00:38:50.746 --> 00:38:52.046
This exists.

00:38:52.846 --> 00:38:56.236
And it was heartbreaking
when I first saw it.

00:38:57.036 --> 00:38:59.736
But then when I'm talking
about getting underneath that,

00:39:00.466 --> 00:39:02.646
what could possibly
drive someone

00:39:02.646 --> 00:39:05.616
to do something like
that, right?

00:39:05.616 --> 00:39:08.606
What could possibly--
I don't know.

00:39:08.606 --> 00:39:11.486
I'm going to choose to
believe that there's no one

00:39:11.586 --> 00:39:13.446
who doesn't want to
breathe clean air.

00:39:13.986 --> 00:39:17.046
No one wants to stand behind;
even the person driving

00:39:17.046 --> 00:39:20.186
that truck doesn't want to stand
behind their truck breathing

00:39:20.186 --> 00:39:22.876
in the black smoke as
it's flying in their face.

00:39:23.356 --> 00:39:25.246
They don't want that.

00:39:25.246 --> 00:39:28.646
What they're raging against is
this mockery and this ridicule

00:39:29.196 --> 00:39:30.356
that I just described.

00:39:31.796 --> 00:39:34.206
It's those of us on
the coast looking

00:39:34.206 --> 00:39:37.596
at good old American values and
saying you're not good enough.

00:39:38.756 --> 00:39:40.036
You are old school.

00:39:40.186 --> 00:39:41.556
You just need to change.

00:39:41.726 --> 00:39:43.116
You just need to
be more like us.

00:39:43.996 --> 00:39:47.246
But when I really get down to it
and I talk to my uncle in Texas,

00:39:47.246 --> 00:39:51.556
I actually kind of got the
way that he saw us, right?

00:39:51.556 --> 00:39:53.096
I can't chop wood.

00:39:53.156 --> 00:39:55.776
Like if I was stuck somewhere,
out in the middle of the woods,

00:39:55.886 --> 00:39:57.386
I would be freaked out.

00:39:57.546 --> 00:39:58.756
I'd be trying to call people

00:39:58.756 --> 00:40:00.676
from my cellphone
with no reception.

00:40:00.966 --> 00:40:02.516
I wouldn't know what
tree this is.

00:40:02.726 --> 00:40:04.416
I wouldn't know what
moss that is.

00:40:04.556 --> 00:40:06.046
I wouldn't know how
to find water.

00:40:06.226 --> 00:40:08.016
I'm basically an
animal in a habitat

00:40:08.396 --> 00:40:09.906
that has no skills whatsoever.

00:40:09.906 --> 00:40:15.156
And for people that grew up with
good old traditional American

00:40:15.156 --> 00:40:18.236
values, that looks
pretty stupid,

00:40:18.546 --> 00:40:21.086
and I can actually
understand that.

00:40:21.086 --> 00:40:24.356
And so finding the
common ground and finding

00:40:24.356 --> 00:40:27.806
where our ideologies are
different, was really important

00:40:27.846 --> 00:40:29.246
to me because then
it helped me find

00:40:29.246 --> 00:40:30.776
out where our ideologies
were the same,

00:40:30.776 --> 00:40:34.076
where there were some things
we actually agreed on,

00:40:34.936 --> 00:40:36.056
because there were no
amount of statistics.

00:40:36.376 --> 00:40:39.776
And this is something that's
really, really, really important

00:40:40.016 --> 00:40:41.766
for movement-based
people to understand.

00:40:42.236 --> 00:40:44.446
Depending on who you're
talking to, there area no amount

00:40:44.506 --> 00:40:45.946
of statistics that are going

00:40:45.946 --> 00:40:49.226
to convince someone
of anything, right?

00:40:49.456 --> 00:40:52.236
Cold hard facts don't do
nothing when you're dealing

00:40:52.236 --> 00:40:53.606
with an ideological difference.

00:40:54.776 --> 00:40:56.116
So start there.

00:40:56.116 --> 00:40:59.136
Figure out if there's just basic
values that you disagree on.

00:40:59.206 --> 00:41:02.216
And then figure out what
that person is protecting

00:41:02.566 --> 00:41:03.576
by keeping those values.

00:41:04.186 --> 00:41:05.236
What is it that they love?

00:41:05.636 --> 00:41:08.326
What is it that's important
to them about their identity,

00:41:08.826 --> 00:41:10.986
that their ideology
helps them to protect?

00:41:11.156 --> 00:41:14.186
And then help them to
protect their identity.

00:41:15.746 --> 00:41:19.516
Help them to understand
that this cold hard facts

00:41:19.516 --> 00:41:22.166
that I'm giving you is
not me saying that the way

00:41:22.166 --> 00:41:25.086
